DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The applied ethics of housing justice has emerged as a significant field within political philosophy over the last decade, responding to housing crises across Western liberal democracies. The domain encompasses philosophical work on housing rights, homelessness, affordability obligations, and housing allocation, bridging normative theory to policy analysis. Key debates center on whether there exists a human right to housing (Wells 2019, Shue 2020), what states owe to those experiencing homelessness (Essert 2016), how affordability obligations should be distributed, and which ethical frameworks—human rights, capabilities, or contractualism—best address housing justice.

The field divides into several interconnected areas: (1) foundational rights-based approaches arguing for basic housing rights (Wells 2019, Shue 2020), often grounded in dignity, autonomy, or basic needs; (2) capabilities-based approaches (Kimhur 2024, Dummer & Neuh\u00e4user 2025) that focus on what people are able to do and be with respect to housing; (3) applied analyses of specific housing phenomena like gentrification (Dawkins 2023, Lloyd 2023) and housing wealth accumulation (Erck 2024); and (4) recent survey work synthesizing the state of the field (Halliday & Meyer 2024). Essert's (2016) work on homelessness and property rights stands as a foundational text examining state obligations to provide shelter. Wells (2019) offers a distinctive liberal account defending a right to autonomous dwelling. Recent work has expanded to include limitarianism applied to housing (Erck 2024) and integration of relational egalitarian concerns (Dummer & Neuh\u00e4user 2025).

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain is central to the research project as it provides the specific applied philosophical literature on housing that contractualist approaches must engage. Understanding existing frameworks—particularly human rights and capabilities approaches—is essential for positioning contractualism's distinctive contributions. The project seeks to show where contractualism adds value and where it faces challenges from these competing frameworks. Papers like Wells (2019), Kimhur (2024), and Dummer & Neuh\u00e4user (2025) represent the state-of-the-art against which a contractualist account must be developed and defended.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While there is substantial work on housing rights and gentrification, there is limited philosophical engagement with: (1) the macroeconomic and fiscal policy dimensions of housing justice (noted by Halliday & Meyer 2024); (2) explicit contractualist frameworks applied to housing (most work draws on human rights, capabilities, or relational egalitarianism); (3) comparative analysis across different housing tenure systems; and (4) philosophical analysis of housing financialization and its justice implications.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis phase should organize papers around competing normative frameworks (rights-based, capabilities, relational equality) while attending to specific issues (homelessness, gentrification, affordability, allocation). Pay special attention to methodological debates about how housing justice should be theorized and whether housing requires a distinctive approach beyond general distributive justice. The recent survey by Halliday & Meyer (2024) provides an excellent roadmap of the field's current state and future directions.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Human rights approach: 6 papers - Housing as basic right grounded in dignity, autonomy, or subsistence (Wells, Shue, Essert)
- Capabilities approach: 4 papers - Housing justice as enabling functionings and capabilities (Kimhur, Dummer & Neuh\u00e4user, Taylor)
- Applied analyses: 5 papers - Specific housing issues through justice lens (gentrification, limitarianism, allocation)
- Survey/overview: 3 papers - State of field and integration (Halliday & Meyer, Shue updated edition)
