  year = {2019},
  volume = {67},
  pages = {406--421},
  doi = {10.1177/0032321718769009},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Wells defends a basic right to housing specific to Western liberal societies, arguing for a positive right to exercise "lease rights" over a self-contained living space of adequate standard for minimum 3 years. Crucially, she argues this is a right to live alone—communal housing imposed by resource scarcity violates basic rights. The account grounds housing rights in autonomy and the distinctive importance of having a stable, private dwelling space.

  RELEVANCE: Wells provides one of the most developed philosophical defenses of a right to housing in recent literature. Her autonomy-based argument offers a clear alternative to contractualist approaches, and her emphasis on the right to autonomous dwelling (not just shelter) raises important questions about what contractualism must deliver. Her focus on Western liberal contexts parallels this project's scope, making direct comparison feasible.

  POSITION: Liberal rights-based approach grounding housing rights in individual autonomy and the value of having one's own dwelling space, with emphasis on stability and privacy as basic rights.
  },
