  doi = {10.1080/14036096.2024.2391424},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Erck develops "housing limitarianism"—the doctrine that it is morally wrong to own excess housing while others lack adequate housing, and that governments should limit excessive housing acquisition/consumption. Building on Robeyns's limitarianism, she employs Rawls's property-owning democracy ideal to argue for dispersing homeownership throughout society. She addresses the apparent tension between increasing affordable housing supply and wildlife habitat preservation.

